Containers are a form of virtualization that allows applications to run in isolated environments while sharing the host operating system.

Unlike traditional virtualization, containers do not require a full OS for each instance, making them lightweight and fast.

For example, Docker containers can start in seconds compared to minutes for virtual machines.

A real-life use case is deploying web applications quickly across multiple environments without configuration issues.

Another example is running multiple applications on the same server without conflicts.

Containers improve resource efficiency, portability, and speed.
